# Approach
1. Initialize a variable count to keep track of the current directory level.
2. Iterate through each string log in the logs array.
3. For each log entry:
- If it is "../" (representing moving up one level in the directory hierarchy), decrement count by 1, but only if count is greater than 0 (to avoid going below the root level).
- If it is "./" (representing staying in the current directory), skip this log entry and continue to the next one.
- For any other log entry, increment count by 1, representing moving into a subdirectory.
4. After processing all log entries, count will represent the minimum number of operations required to reach the final directory.
5. Return the count as the result.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
The code iterates through each log entry in the logs array, so the time complexity is O(n), where n is the number of log entries.

- Space complexity:
The code uses a single integer variable count, so the space complexity is O(1), as it doesn't depend on the size of the input.
# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int minOperations(String[] logs) {
        int count=0;
        for(String log: logs){
            if(log.equals("../")) count=count==0?0:count-1;
            else if(log.equals("./")) continue;
            else count++;
        }
        return count;
    }
}
```

