solutions.content:
A N-ary tree is a good fit for this problem because we are representing a family tree where each parent may have 0, 1, ..., N children.  

What makes this N-ary tree special is that the children are stored in a list, because the order they were born matters.  

Thus **the order of inheritance** (our answer) **is simply a pre-order traversal** (visit root, then first child, then second child, ..., then last child) **of the N-ary tree**.  

Hope this helps!

```python
class Node(object):
    def __init__(self, name):
        self.name = name
        self.children = [] # Use a list to store children, because birth order matters

class Nary_Tree(object):
    def __init__(self, kingName):
        self.root = Node(kingName)
        self.family_tree = {kingName : self.root} # Use a hash-map for O(1) lookup: name -> node
        self.dead = set()                         # Keep a set of all people who have died

    def birth(self, parent_name, child_name):
        parent_node = self.family_tree[parent_name] # Go to the parent node
        child_node = Node(child_name)               # Create a child node
        parent_node.children.append(child_node)     # Add child to parent's list of children
        self.family_tree[child_name] = child_node   # Add child to hash-map for O(1) lookup by child's name (in case the child gives birth later)

    def inheritance_order(self):
		'''Pre-order Traversal of the Nary-Tree and return names
		in the order they are visited (if they are not dead)'''
        order = []
        def helper(node):
            nonlocal order
            if node.name not in self.dead:
                order.append(node.name)
            for i,child in enumerate(node.children):
                helper(node.children[i])
        helper(self.root)
        return order

class ThroneInheritance:

    def __init__(self, kingName: str):
        self.tree = Nary_Tree(kingName)

    def birth(self, parentName: str, childName: str) -> None:
        self.tree.birth(parentName, childName)

    def death(self, name: str) -> None:
        self.tree.dead.add(name)

    def getInheritanceOrder(self) -> List[str]:
        return self.tree.inheritance_order()
```

