# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Similar to knapsack problem
For each request we choose to fulfil it or ignore it
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(2 ^ N)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(N)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
- Where $$N$$ is $$request.length$$

# Code
```C++ []
class Solution {
public:
    int f(int i, vector<vector<int>>& requests, vector<int> &freq, int count = 0) {
        if(i == requests.size()) {
            for(int j: freq) if(j != 0) return 0; // net transfer != 0
            return count; // net tranasfer == 0
        }

        int notTake = f(i + 1, requests, freq, count);

        freq[requests[i][0]]--, freq[requests[i][1]]++; // Update the freq
        int take = f(i + 1, requests, freq, count + 1);
        freq[requests[i][0]]++, freq[requests[i][1]]--; // Backtracking

        return max(take, notTake);
    }
    int maximumRequests(int n, vector<vector<int>>& requests) {
        vector<int> freq(n, 0);
        return f(0, requests, freq);
    }
};
```
