solutions.content:
# Intuition

Disclaimer: This is just a Java implementation of the following code. It took me some time to understand the ideas so I wanted to hopefully help people struggling as me. If you liked this tex PLEASE consider upvoting the original article! https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-number-of-achievable-transfer-requests/solutions/867597/c-o-ve-2-time-solution-8ms/

Note: There are some enhancements and alternatives that can be done in the code (as dfs to identify loops). I chose to keep as close to the original as possible to keep this article as an explanation to the original.

The main idea of the algorithm:
1. Find a loop positive.
2. Invert the direction of the vertices in the loop and transform the vertices weights into negative values.
3. Go to step 1.

Why does it work?

Imagine that some vertices of a path X are part of multiple loops, so we have a path A of vertices that is smaller or equal to another path B. Arbitrarily we can create a draw with representing it:


![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/afff76d7-ef84-4ff7-b826-3b2da322ae05_1688423825.643032.png)

Imagine that we are searching for positive loops and you find the one with path $$X+A$$. Lets do step 2.

This leaves us with a path of weight: $$TOTAL_1=ABS(X)+ABS(A)$$

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/56ae71b0-2057-4d4c-aae5-f73021039208_1688424456.367311.png)

Now notice that $$\tilde{A}+B$$ now form a loop, and as mentioned in the begining path B is greater than A, so the loop is positive (notice that if the path were otherwise smaller or equal we would ignore the loop as it is not positive). Then lets repeat step 2.

This leaves us with a path of weight: $$TOTAL_2=ABS(X)+ABS(B)=ABS(X)+ABS(A)+ABS(\tilde{A})+ABS(B)=TOTAL_1+ABS(\tilde{A})+ABS(B)$$

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/de2e35b6-3edf-4199-8aab-54c606f85f7d_1688424609.3795946.png)

Once again we end up with a loop $$A+\tilde{B}$$, but as A is smaller than B this loop is negative, so we can stop. This is also the graph we would have ended if we had found the loop $$X+B$$ instead of $$X+A$$

Note: the is an IF verification `d[v] >= d[u] + w` in the middle of the code that prevents us from mistaking situations as below with positive loops. Notice that at the moment the first repeated node/vertice appears the path decreased the value below or equal to the original, and the if prevents us from continuing.

The situation such as when we begin in the higest node.

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/19b8590f-67da-475b-aa91-0a78dbb5e1e0_1688427291.1960318.png)


# Approach
- Graph Theory
- Bellman Ford

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$O(VE^2)$$ <- Bellman-Ford is O(VE), and you can have at most E loops, because at every outer loop you remove at least one vertice from the pool.
  - Note: Now, suppose the edges have different positive weights. In the worst-case scenario, every time we find a cycle, we reduce the total positive weight by at least 1. This is because finding a cycle and reversing it reduces the total weight in the graph: the cycle's weight is added to the answer and then subtracted from the graph.
Sometimes a path on the cycle was already negative, so this part becomes positive. I mention this in case you think that the actual min value subtracted is the min weight instead of 1, as it can be the diference of edges.
Therefore, with different weights the outer loop will run at most W times, where W is the total weight of all positive-weighted edges in the graph. If the weights are all positive and the smallest weight is 1, then W is at least equal to E. Therefore the time complexity becomes O(VEW).

- Space complexity:
$$O(V+E)$$

# Code
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/f1896ee1-0857-4419-b825-1cf270ea83e5_1688424984.3026135.png)

```java
class Solution {

    // Define the Edge class with four attributes
    class Edge {
        int v, w, sw, rev;
        public Edge(int v, int w, int sw, int rev) {
            this.v = v;  // destination vertex
            this.w = w;  // weight of the edge
            this.sw = sw;  // switch to control if the edge is being considered (1 = yes, 0 = no)
            this.rev = rev;  // the reverse edge index in the adjacency list of v
        }
    }

    public int maximumRequests(int n, int[][] requests) {
        // Create the adjacency list for graph representation
        ArrayList<ArrayList<Edge>> g = new ArrayList<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            g.add(new ArrayList<>());
        }

        int ans = 0; // Initialize the answer as 0
        // Build the graph from the request list
        for (int[] e : requests) {
            int u = e[0], v = e[1]; // u = start vertex, v = end vertex
            if (u == v) {
                ans++; // If a request is made to the same computer, increment ans
                continue;
            }
            // If request is made to a different computer, create edges in the graph
            g.get(u).add(new Edge(v, 1, 1, g.get(v).size()));
            g.get(v).add(new Edge(u, -1, 0, g.get(u).size()-1));
        }

        // While loop to keep finding positive-weighted cycles
        while (true) {
            int[] d = new int[n], pv = new int[n], pe = new int[n], cnt = new int[n]; // Arrays to store shortest path value, previous vertex, previous edge, count of edges
            boolean[] inq = new boolean[n]; // Array to store if a vertex is in queue
            Queue<Integer> bf = new LinkedList<>(); // Queue to perform the Breadth-first search

            // Add all vertices in the queue and mark them as in queue
            for(int i=0; i<n; ++i){
                bf.add(i);
                inq[i] = true;
            }

            int ncv = -1; // Initialize the cycle vertex as -1 (indicating not found)
            // Perform the Breadth-first search to find a cycle (Bellman-Ford)
            while (!bf.isEmpty()) {
                int u = bf.poll();
                inq[u] = false;
                // For each edge from vertex u, relax the edge
                for (int i = 0; i < g.get(u).size(); ++i) {
                    Edge e = g.get(u).get(i);
                    int v = e.v, w = e.w, sw = e.sw;
                    // Skip if the edge is not switch on or doesn't provide a bigger path
                    if (sw == 0 || d[v] >= d[u] + w) continue;
                    // If a bigger path is found, update the path
                    d[v] = d[u] + w;
                    pv[v] = u; pe[v] = i;
                    // If the vertex is not in queue, add it
                    if (!inq[v]) {
                        // If we have relaxed edges from the vertex n times, we have found a cycle
                        if (++cnt[v] == n) {
                            ncv = v; // Update the cycle vertex
                            break;
                        }
                        bf.add(v);
                        inq[v] = true;
                    }
                }
                //System.out.println(u+" "+Arrays.toString(d)+" "+Arrays.toString(pv));
                if(ncv != -1) break; // If a cycle is found, break the loop
            }

            // If no cycle is found, break the loop
            if (ncv == -1) break;
            boolean[] vis = new boolean[n]; // Array to store if a vertex is visited
            // Find the cycle by going through the previous vertices
            for(; !vis[ncv]; ncv = pv[ncv]){
                vis[ncv] = true;
            }

            int u = ncv; // Start from the vertex in the cycle
            // Go through the cycle to reverse the cycle and update the answer
            do {
                int p = pv[u], i = pe[u]; // Get the previous vertex and edge
                ans += g.get(p).get(i).w; // Add the weight to the answer
                g.get(p).get(i).sw = 0; // Switch off the edge
                g.get(u).get(g.get(p).get(i).rev).sw = 1; // Switch on the reverse edge
                u = p; // Move to the previous vertex
            } while(u != ncv);
        }
        return ans; // Return the maximum number of requests that can be achieved
    }
}
```

