solutions.content:
# Intuition
This problem can be solved using min cost flow, potentially on larger graphs. For this particular problem size, it is an overkill. I am doing this just to practice.

# Approach
Consider the graph induced by the request, mark all edges with cost -1.
Also two extra nodes source and target that is not connected to anything else, we can find the minimum cost flow between source and target. Obviously the flow is going to be zero, but the minimum cost part can help us to drive to maximize request satisfaction as part of the cost minimization process.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
$$ O(n^2C) $$, where $$ C $$ is the number of requests that could be satisfied. I am not particularly happy with this time bound, but I also don't bother to implement minimum mean cycle cancellation which is usually much more complex and also slower in practice. I would be very wrong here since I don't have much experiences implementing min cost flow.

- Space complexity:
$$ O(E) $$，where $$ E $$ is the number of edges (i.e. requests)

# Code
```
import (
	"fmt"
)

func maximumRequests(n int, requests [][]int) int {
	cost := make([]int, n+1)
	next := make([]int, n+1)
	pred := make([]int, n+1)
	flip := make([]bool, len(requests))
	infinite := 100
	count := 0

	for {	// Keep trying to cancel cycles
	    // The plan is to use Bellman Ford to find a negative cycle, eliminate it, and the reverse to
		// the residual graph, and repeat until we cannot find one.

		// The problem with Bellman Ford is that it can only find negative cycle reachable from a source
		// and we don't have a source, so I added this node n as a virtual source that connects to every node

		// Now we can initialize the cost vector, with the node reachable at cost 0 and every other unreachable		
		for i := 0; i < n+1; i++ {
			cost[i] = infinite
		}
		cost[n] = 0 

		for round := 0; round < n+1; round++ { // Bellman Ford iterations
			// Initialize the costs for the next round with the current values
			for i := 0; i < n+1; i++ {
				next[i] = cost[i]
			}
			// Relax all the virtual edges from source to every node
			for s := 0; s < n; s++ {
				if cost[n] != infinite && cost[s] > cost[n] {
					next[s] = cost[n]
					pred[s] = n
				}
			}
			// Relax all the given edges
			for e := 0; e < len(requests); e++ {
				src := requests[e][0]
				dst := requests[e][1]
				weight := -1
				// Note that an edge could be flipped because of the negative cycle cancellation.
				if flip[e] {
					src, dst, weight = dst, src, -weight
				}
				if cost[src] != infinite && cost[dst] > cost[src]+weight {
					next[dst] = cost[src] + weight
					// Here we are doing something slightly unconventional here. I am saving the edge
					// as the predecesor of the node for the cycle cancellation purpose. Obviously we can
					// easily get to the actual predecesor node given the edge but not vice versa.
					pred[dst] = e
				}
			}
			// Once we are done, swap the cost and next to beging the next iteration.
			cost, next = next, cost
		}

		// Since the graph has only n+1 nodes (including the virtual source). Any path with n 
		// edges must have a cycle and therefore longer than the shortest path if the cycle is 
		// positive. If we find any cost changes during the n and n+1 round, that must be due to
		// a negative cycle
		found := false
		node := 0
		for i := 0; i < n+1; i++ {
			if cost[i] < next[i] {
				found = true
				node = i
			}
		}
		if found {
			// Now we have found some node that has a change in cost, back tracking the edges
			// to find the cycle. During the walk, mark node as seen and keep the edges in a stack
			cur := node
			seen := make([]int, n)
			edgeStack := []int{}
			for {
				seen[cur] = 1
				e := pred[cur]
				src := requests[e][0]
				dst := requests[e][1]
				if flip[e] {
					src, dst = dst, src
				}
				edgeStack = append(edgeStack, e)
				cur = src
				if seen[cur] == 1 {
					// Now that we have found the cycle, pop the edges and flip them all
					// Count the number of edges that is flipped from the original configuration
					// These are the requests that could be satisfied from the problem definition
					//
					// Note that the virtual edges from the source can never be part of a cycle so 
					// we won't accidentally count those.
					for i := len(edgeStack) - 1; i >= 0; i-- {
						e := edgeStack[i]
						src := requests[e][0]
						dst := requests[e][1]
						if flip[e] {
							src, dst = dst, src
							count = count - 1
						} else {
							count = count + 1
						}
						flip[e] = !flip[e]

						if dst == cur {
							break
						}
					}
					break
				}
			}
		} else {
			// In case we cannot find a negative cycle in the residual graph, we are done
			// the flow cannot be optimized further for cost
			break
		}
	}

	return count
}

