# Intuition

The task can be easily represented as a special case of minimum-cost [circulation problem](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circulation_problem). Note: in case you are not familiar with what flows and circulations are, my explanation will probably be rather hard to understand, sorry.
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
Technically we compute maximum-cost circulation, but the approach does not change.

For every request `[a, b]` we create two edges:
- "Forward" edge - `a` to `b` of capacity 1 and weight 1.
- "Backward" edge - `b` to `a` of capacity 0 and weight -1.

At every step of the algorithm we try to find a cycle of positive weight using Bellman-Ford algorithm. In case a cycle is found, we perform augmentation similar to max-flow algorithms (moving capacity from used edges into the opposite direction edges).
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n^3\cdot |requests|)$$, but in reality somewhat faster. If we were to store edge list instead of adjacency matrix, the complexity would be improved to $$O(n \cdot |requests|^2)$$.
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n^2)$$, but theoretically could do $$O(n+|requests|)$$ using edge lists.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> capFwd, capBwd;

    int maximumRequests(int n, vector<vector<int>>& requests) {
        int result = 0;
        capFwd.assign(n, vector<int>(n));
        capBwd = capFwd;
        for (auto& r: requests) {
            int from = r[0];
            int to = r[1];
            if (from == to) {
                result += 1;
            } else {
                capFwd[from][to] += 1;
            }
        }

        vector<int> from;
        vector<int> dist;

        for (;;) {
            dist.assign(n, 0);
            from.assign(n, -1);
            int changedIdx = -1;

            // n steps of Bellman-Ford algorithm
            // to detect if there are cycles of positive weight.
            for (int step = 0; step < n; ++step) {
                changedIdx = -1;
                for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
                    for (int j = 0; j < n; ++j) {
                        if (capFwd[i][j] > 0 && dist[j] >= dist[i]) {
                            changedIdx = j;
                            dist[j] = dist[i] - 1;
                            from[j] = i;
                        }
                        if (capBwd[i][j] > 0 && dist[j] >= dist[i] + 2) {
                            changedIdx = j;
                            dist[j] = dist[i] + 1;
                            from[j] = i;
                        }
                    }
                }
                if (changedIdx == -1) {
                    return result;
                }
            }

            // Tortoise and hare algorithm:
            // finds a point on the cycle.
            for (int i = from[changedIdx]; i != changedIdx; ) {
                i = from[from[i]];
                changedIdx = from[changedIdx];
            }

            // Path augmentation
            int cur = changedIdx;
            do {
                int next = from[cur];
                if (capFwd[next][cur] > 0) {
                    result += 1;
                    capFwd[next][cur] -= 1;
                    capBwd[cur][next] += 1;
                } else {
                    result -= 1;
                    capFwd[cur][next] += 1;
                    capBwd[next][cur] -= 1;
                }
                cur = next;
            } while (cur != changedIdx);
        }
    }
};
```

