# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
This problem can be deceiving at the first look because it talks about connections and indegree/outdegree concept. But it is a variation of "Partition to K Equal Sum Subsets" where the partitioning can be thought of as **making sure that equal number of residents participate to move into or out of the building**.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We will use a simple backtracking based approach. 

We will cater each and every request and track the total net flow (total incomers and outgoers in each building) that happens with each of the request. At the end we see if net flow has remained constant for each building (0) and accordingly save the answers.

Trackers used:
1. `buildingNetFlow` to keep track of the net inflow outflow of buildings
2. `acceptedRequests` to keep tally of the accepted request in the current stack space
3. `requestNo` to keep track of the current request being catered
4. `ans` stores the maximum possible applications that fit the criteria

Go through every single application and make recursive calls on:

 **Accepting the application-** We will increment "`acceptedApplications`" by 1, and increment "`requestNo`" by 1 (to move to next request), store the specific `incoming` and `outgoing` persons and set the `buildingNetFlow` accordingly.


**Rejecting the application-** We will increment "`requestNo`" by 1 (to move to next request)

Our base case for each recursive call would be- Reaching the end of the `requests` list. We will check if the `buildingNetFlow` satisfies our condition that *"net flow across all buildings is 0".*

If it satisfies we store the max till that instance into `ans`. 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(K*2^n), where K is the tree stack, n is the number of applications

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N), where N is the number of buildings

#### Further Optimization
This solution can be further optimized by memoization (DP), storing the each individual combination of decisions to derive the answers for later recursion that merge to the same path.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:

    void processApplications( vector<vector<int>>&requests,
        vector<int> buildingNetFlow,
        int acceptedRequests,
        int totalRequests,
        int requestNo,
        int&ans
    ){
        if(requestNo == totalRequests){
            //check for the validity
            for(auto it: buildingNetFlow){
                if(it != 0) return;
            }
            //store the minimum 
            ans = max(ans, acceptedRequests);
            return;
        }

        //call the recursion
        processApplications(requests, buildingNetFlow, acceptedRequests, totalRequests, requestNo+1, ans);

        // accept the request 
        int outgoing = requests[requestNo][0];
        int incoming = requests[requestNo][1];
        buildingNetFlow[outgoing]--;
        buildingNetFlow[incoming]++;

        // call the recursion
        processApplications(requests, buildingNetFlow, acceptedRequests+1, totalRequests, requestNo+1, ans);

        return;

    }

    int maximumRequests(int n, vector<vector<int>>& requests) {
        //currently all buildings are full and proportioned 
        vector<int> buildingNetFlow(n, 0);
        int totalRequests = requests.size();
        int acceptedRequests = 0;
        int ans = INT_MIN;
        processApplications(requests, buildingNetFlow, acceptedRequests, totalRequests, 0, ans);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

