# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
It's a simple pick, notPick recursion. We need to select maximum number of requests..

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Keep an array to track the number  of changes, in base condition if all the elements of array are 0 return 0, else INT_MIN, so that it can't be selected.
2. The index of building represents the changes, if we pick then build[from]-- , build[to]++;
3. Then before not picking build[from]++ , build[to]--; 

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(2^n * n) 
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n+logn) including the recursion call stack.

# Code
```
class Solution {
    vector<int>build;
    int solve(int i , vector<vector<int>>& requests){
        if(i==requests.size()){
            for(auto it : build) if(it) return -1e8;
            return 0;
        }
        // pick
        int x = requests[i][0];
        int y = requests[i][1];

        build[x]--;
        build[y]++;
        int pick  = 1 + solve(i+1 , requests);
        build[x]++;
        build[y]--;
        // not pick
        int notpick = solve(i+1 , requests);

        return max(pick , notpick);

    }
public:
    int maximumRequests(int n, vector<vector<int>>& requests) {
        build.resize(n);
        return solve(0, requests);
    }
};
```

