# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We just have to process all combinations of requests and look for those combinations which have net employee transfer as zero.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Different combinations are equivalent to different subsequences which can be formed using 2 methods:
1). Backtracking (take and not take method), 
2). Bitmasking
We will go with second one.
# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(2^n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumRequests(int n, vector<vector<int>>& requests) {
        int s=requests.size();
        int res=0;
        int count=0;
        for(int i=0;i<(1<<s);i++){
            vector<int>in(n,0);
            vector<int>out(n,0);
            for(int j=0;j<s;j++){
                if(i & (1<<j)){
                    out[requests[j][0]]++;
                    in[requests[j][1]]++;
                    count++;
                }
            }
            if(in==out) res=max(res,count);
            count=0;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

