# Intuition
Backtracking & DFS

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Skip requests[i]:
The algorithm starts by skipping the current request, requests[i], and makes a recursive call to dfs(i + 1, processedReqs, requests, degree). This recursive call allows the algorithm to move on to the next request without making any changes to the degree array.

Process requests[i]:
After skipping the current request, the algorithm then proceeds to process it. This involves updating the degree array to reflect the movement of employees between buildings:

Decrement the degree of the building the employee is moving from (--degree[requests[i][0]]).
Increment the degree of the building the employee is moving to (++degree[requests[i][1]]).
The algorithm then makes a recursive call to dfs(i + 1, processedReqs + 1, requests, degree). This recursive call explores the remaining requests with the updated degree array, considering the effect of processing the current request.

After the recursive call, the algorithm reverts the changes made to the degree array by incrementing the degree of the building the employee is moving from and decrementing the degree of the building the employee is moving to:

Increment the degree of the building the employee is moving from (++degree[requests[i][0]]).
Decrement the degree of the building the employee is moving to (--degree[requests[i][1]]).
This step is necessary to restore the degree array to its original state before exploring other possibilities.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(2^N).

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(N)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int maximumRequests(int n, int[][] requests) {
        backtrack(0,0,requests,new int[n]);
        return ans;
    }
    int ans=0;
    private void backtrack(int index,int p,int[][] requests,int[] degree){
       if(requests.length==index){
           if(Arrays.stream(degree).allMatch(d -> d == 0)){
               ans=Math.max(ans,p);
           }
           return;
       }
     backtrack(index+1,p,requests,degree);
     --degree[requests[index][0]];
     ++degree[requests[index][1]];
     backtrack(index+1,p+1,requests,degree);
     ++degree[requests[index][0]];
     --degree[requests[index][1]];

    }
}
```

