# Approach
 We have to **go through each subset of the requests array**
- because we have to ignore some of the requests and accept some so that all the accepted ones can be performed
    We want the subset that has max size and all the requests in it are possible
-  **How do we check if the subset has all requests that can be performed ?**
- We have to ensure that in the inAndOut array the net remains 0 for each building
- Because "*All buildings are full, so a list of requests is achievable only if for each building, the net change in employee transfers is zero.*"

- If all the building dont have net headCount = 0 then that sbuset is not possible else if all the elem are 0 in inAndOut we simply update the ans and return


# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int ans = 0;
    void solve(int currReq , vector<vector<int>>& requests, 
    vector<int>& inAndOut , int reqTaken)
    {
        //base case
        if(currReq == requests.size())
        {
            for(auto it : inAndOut)
            {
                if(it!=0) return;
            }
            ans=max(ans,reqTaken);
            return;
        }

        //The line below is just an OPTIMISATION , code can work without it
        if (reqTaken + (requests.size() - currReq) < ans) {
            return;
        }

        //We dont take the request OR we leave it
        solve(currReq + 1 , requests , inAndOut , reqTaken);


        //Now when we pick the request
        inAndOut[requests[currReq][1]]++;
        inAndOut[requests[currReq][0]]--;

        solve(currReq + 1 , requests , inAndOut , reqTaken+1);

        //While backtracking reverse these changes
        inAndOut[requests[currReq][1]]--;
        inAndOut[requests[currReq][0]]++;


    }
    int maximumRequests(int n, vector<vector<int>>& requests) {
        vector<int> inAndOut(n);
        solve(0,requests,inAndOut,0);
        return ans;
    }
};
```

